statement.p:
Find the nullity of the matrix

					A= \mat{
					1 1 1 1;
					2 3 4 5
					}

answer.p:
Elementary row operations do not change the nullspace. Let us convert A to reduced row echelon form.

				\mat{
				1 1 1 1;
				2 3 4 5
				}
				\quad\xrightarrow{}\quad
				\mat{
				1 1 1 1;
				0 1 2 3
				}
				\quad\xrightarrow{}\quad
				\mat{
				1 0 -1 2;
				0 1 2 3
				}

				The parameteric forms of the solutions of Ax=0 are

				\syseq{
				x_1 \+ \. - x_3 - 2x_4 = 0;
				\. \+ x_2 + 2x_3 + 3x_4 = 0
				}
				\quad\implies\quad
				\syseq{
				x_1 = \. \+ x_3 + 2x_4;
				x_2 = \. - 2x_3 - 3x_4
				}

				Vectors \left\{\vec{1 -2 1 0},\; \vec{2 -3 0 1}\right\} form a basis for \Nul(A). Thus nullity of the matrix is 2.

statement.p:
Find the rank of the matrix

					A= \mat{
					-1 0 -1 2;
					2 0 2 0;
					1 0 1 -1
					}

answer.p:
Elementary row operations do not change the row space. Let us convert A to row echelon form:


					\mat{
					-1 0 -1 2;
					2 0 2 0;
					1 0 1 -1
					}
					\quad\xrightarrow{}\quad
					\mat{
					-1 0 -1 2;
					0 0 0 4;
					1 0 1 -1
					}
					\quad\xrightarrow{}\quad
					\mat{
					-1 0 -1 2;
					0 0 0 4;
					0 0 0 1
					}


					\quad\xrightarrow{}\quad
					\mat{
					-1 0 -1 2;
					0 0 0 0;
					0 0 0 1
					}
					\quad\xrightarrow{}\quad
					\mat{
					-1 0 -1 2;
					0 0 0 1;
					0 0 0 0
					}
					\quad\xrightarrow{}\quad
					\mat{
					1 0 1 -2;
					0 0 0 1;
					0 0 0 0 
					}


				Vectors \left\{\vec{1 0 1 -2}, \vec{0 0 0 1}\right\} form a basis for the row space of A. Thus the rank of A is 2.
